Fixtures and Decorators

1. @pytest.fixture(scope="module")
def setup():
    print("Setting up the DB Connection")
    yield
    print("Quitting up the DB Connection")   -- code is for the referring purpose

@pytest.fixture(scope="function")
def before():
    print("launcing the browser before the test case")
    yield
    print("close the browser after the test case")

2. def test_login(setup, before): -- we can do this to use the fixtures. We can do it in an another ways as well.
    assert True
    print("Forcefully pass the testcase")

3. @pytest.mark.usefixtures("setup", "before") - This is the another way to pass the methods using the fixtures and markers.


Markers

1. pytest test_markers.py -s -v -k "reg" - By using the string, we can deselect the test cases and run the test cases that we want
2. We can do it by using the makers concept as well. That's we are going to see in this video
3. pytest test_markers.py -s -v -m "functional" is the command to run in the terminal.
4. pytest.mark.functional - we can give the name anything that we wanted instead of the functional
5. we will get the warning summary like this:
test_markers.py:3
  C:\Users\dsam3\Pytest\pytest_learning\test_markers.py:3: PytestUnknownMarkWarning: Unknown pytest.mark.functinal - is this a typo?  You can register custom marks to avoid this warning - for details, see https://docs.pytest.org/en/stable/how-to/mark.html
    @pytest.mark.functinal
 6. we need to register it in the ".ini" file - [pytest]
markers =
        functinal
        dinosaur
        regression -- create this in an .ini file to ignore the warning summary
7. we can also skip the test cases as well intentionally - @pytest.mark.skip(reason="I don't want to run")

